<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Practical Applications</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
<P>Read pages 23 and 24 of your lecture notes to see the exponential function applied to bacterial growth and population decay.   Now work through <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 2 17 c~?">2-17 section c</a>.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>The Exponential Function</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
<P>Having considered exponential functions now work on <B>The Exponential Function </B>in <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 2 17 d~?">2-17 section d</a> and <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 2 17 e 1~?">section e tutorial 1</a>.   You need only complete Tutorial 1 in section e.</P>

<P>The base <B>e </B>is very convenient when we wish to express exponential growth (or decrease) in algebraic terms.</P>

<P>e.g. Suppose a population consists of 1000 cells at time t = 0 hours.   If we are told that the population is increasing exponentially and has an instantaneous rate of growth of 69% per hour, we can immediately write down a formula giving the size of the population at any given time t hours, namely</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">P(t) = 1000e<SUP>0.69t</P>
</SUP>
<P>Page 26 in your lecture notes gives a further example.   Pages 27-33 illustrate graphically <B>the exponential function.</P></B>

